{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/991"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.13,0.13,0.34,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51362"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/991"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36652"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3363"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14737"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51362"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with a one-week history of jaundice, dark urine and general malaise. She has no significant medical history apart from a chest infection four weeks ago for which she was prescribed a five-day course of amoxicillin-clavulanate. She does not take any regular medications. She drinks one glass of wine per day and does not smoke. On examination, she appears well but obviously jaundiced. Her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are no other abnormal physical findings. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin 62 \u00b5mol/L (2-24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT 68 U/L (\u0026lt;60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP 410 U/L (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 160 U/L (\u0026lt;55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 180 U/L (\u0026lt;45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR 1.2 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 128 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 7.8 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular observation alone","Cholestyramine","Prednisolone","Ursodeoxycholic acid","N-acetylcysteine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical presentation is most consistent with amoxicillin-clavulanic acid-induced cholestatic hepatitis. Amoxicillin-clavulanate is a well-known cause of drug-induced liver injury (DILI), typically presenting about three weeks after initiation of the drug. The liver function tests show a cholestatic pattern, which is characteristic of this type of DILI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eregular observation alone\u003C/strong\u003E. Most cases of drug-induced liver injury will resolve spontaneously with expectant management. No specific medications have been shown to improve outcomes in DILI. An abdominal ultrasound to exclude biliary obstruction would also be appropriate as part of the initial workup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholestyramine\u003C/strong\u003E is used to bind bile acids in the gut and prevent their reabsorption. It may be used to treat pruritus in cholestatic liver disease. It can also be used as a cholesterol-lowering agent in patients with primary hypercholesterolaemia. However, it has no role in the management of drug-induced liver injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used in the management of drug-induced liver injury. While it may be considered in the setting of hypersensitivity reactions leading to liver injury, there is no evidence to support its use in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrsodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat primary biliary cholangitis and intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy. However, it does not have any proven benefit in the management of drug-induced liver injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the management of paracetamol overdose to prevent hepatotoxicity. It is not indicated in the treatment of amoxicillin-clavulanate induced liver injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management in this case is recognizing the likely cause of the liver injury, discontinuing the offending medication (which has already occurred), and monitoring the patient\u0027s clinical status and liver function tests. Most patients with drug-induced liver injury will improve spontaneously over time without specific interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of drug-induced liver injury will resolve spontaneously with expectant management.","Amoxicillin-clavulanate is a common cause of drug-induced liver injury, typically presenting with a cholestatic pattern."],"references":["Ghabril M et al. Drug-induced liver injury: a clinical update. Curr Opin Gastroenterol 2010 Feb 27; 26:222."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36652"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36652"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-24T11:28:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-24T11:29:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"991"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51362"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3363"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","